In Java, String methods are built-in functions provided by the java.lang.String class
that allow programmers to manipulate, search, inspect, and compare sequences of characters.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

METHOD                          | RETURN TYPE | DESCRIPTION
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
length()                        | int         | Returns the number of characters in the string.
charAt(int index)               | char        | Returns the character at the specified index.
substring(int begin)            | String      | Extracts a substring starting from the specified index.
toLowerCase() / toUpperCase()   | String      | Converts the string to all lowercase or uppercase letters.
equals(Object obj)              | boolean     | Compares contents of two strings for exact equality.
equalsIgnoreCase(String str)    | boolean     | Compares contents for equality, ignoring case differences.
contains(CharSequence s)        | boolean     | Checks if the string contains a specific sequence.
indexOf(String str)             | int         | Returns the index of the first occurrence of a substring.
trim() / strip()                | String      | Removes leading and trailing whitespaces.
replace(char old, char new)     | String      | Replaces all occurrences of an old character with a new one.



------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


public class StringMethodsDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Base string initialization
        String message = "  Hello, Java Programming!  ";
        System.out.println("Original String: '" + message + "'");

        // 1. Check Length
        int len = message.length();
        System.out.println("1. Length: " + len);

        // 2. Trim Whitespace
        String trimmed = message.trim();
        System.out.println("2. Trimmed: '" + trimmed + "'");

        // 3. Convert Case
        System.out.println("3. Upper Case: " + trimmed.toUpperCase());
        System.out.println("   Lower Case: " + trimmed.toLowerCase());

        // 4. Extract Character by Index
        char firstChar = trimmed.charAt(0);
        System.out.println("4. Character at index 0: " + firstChar);

        // 5. Extract Substring
        // Takes characters from index 7 up to (but not including) index 11
        String sub = trimmed.substring(7, 11); 
        System.out.println("5. Substring (7 to 11): " + sub);

        // 6. Search within String
        boolean hasJava = trimmed.contains("Java");
        int index = trimmed.indexOf("Prog");
        System.out.println("6. Contains 'Java'?: " + hasJava);
        System.out.println("   Index of 'Prog': " + index);

        // 7. Replace Text
        String replaced = trimmed.replace("Java", "World");
        System.out.println("7. Replaced String: " + replaced);

        // 8. Equality Comparisons
        String s1 = "java";
        String s2 = "JAVA";
        System.out.println("8. Exact equals (java vs JAVA): " + s1.equals(s2));
        System.out.println("   Equals ignoring case: " + s1.equalsIgnoreCase(s2));
    }
}



Output:

Original String: '  Hello, Java Programming!  '
1. Length: 28
2. Trimmed: 'Hello, Java Programming!'
3. Upper Case: HELLO, JAVA PROGRAMMING!
   Lower Case: hello, java programming!
4. Character at index 0: H
5. Substring (7 to 11): Java
6. Contains 'Java'?: true
   Index of 'Prog': 12
7. Replaced String: Hello, World Programming!
8. Exact equals (java vs JAVA): false
   Equals ignoring case: true




