# Core Concepts of Java Strings

To work effectively with strings, you must understand how Java manages them under the hood.

- Immutability: String objects cannot be changed once created. Methods like replace() do not modify the original string; they return a brand new one.
- String Pool: Java optimizes memory by storing one copy of each literal string in a special memory area called the String Constant Pool.
- Heap Memory: Creating a string using the new keyword (e.g., new String("Java")) bypasses the pool and forces the creation of a brand new object in standard heap memory.


